    <section class="content __pool-and-spa-guides/5-steps-to-prepare-your-pool-for-winter ">
    
                    <div class="content-block">
                <h1 class="h3">5 Steps To Prepare Your Pool For Winter</h1>
            </div>

        
     
                                <div class="content-block blog-styling">
                            <p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Now that autumn is coming and your pool usage has probably declined, it is time to start thinking about how to <a href="closing-pool-for-winter">get your pool ready for the cooler climates of winter</a>.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Although our winter climates are not harsh enough for our pools to start freezing over, preparing your pool for an extended period without use can ensure that your pool is healthy and ready for the warmer seasons of spring and summer.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Winterising focuses on preventing algae growth and water stagnation. Follow these 5 simple steps to make sure that your pool is healthy and ready to use when the warmer seasons come rolling around!</span></p>
            </div>

        
     
                    <!-- Ten Steps -->
<div class="content-block">
    <div class="slider">
        <p class="heading"></p>
        <div class="owl-carousel steps">
                            <div class="slides">
                    <div class="img"><img src="https://s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com/zodiac-au-2/Blog/5_steps_winter_prep/5_steps_prep_clean.jpg" alt="Give it a deep clean" /></div>
                    <div class="text">
                        <p class="__blue">Give it a deep clean</p>
                        <p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Thoroughly scrub through your pool tiles, making sure that you have not forgotten any corners and remove any scale and bacteria that might break down and help algae to grow. Don&rsquo;t forget about cleaning the skimmer baskets and your pump&rsquo;s lint basket too! </span></p></p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                            <div class="slides">
                    <div class="img"><img src="https://s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com/zodiac-au-2/Blog/5_steps_winter_prep/pool_testing_strip.jpg" alt="Balance the water and shock your pool" /></div>
                    <div class="text">
                        <p class="__blue">Balance the water and shock your pool</p>
                        <p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In order to prevent an algae build up, you will need to ensure that the pH of your pool sits in between 7.2 and 7.6. You can easily check your pool&rsquo;s pH level by taking a water sample from elbow deep and add the appropriate Chemical from our </span><a href="../pure-balance"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pure Balance Range</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> to bring the pool to the correct level. &ldquo;Shocking&rdquo; your pool helps remove organic and inorganic waste including sweat, sunscreen lotion, bird dropping and dead bugs. It also ensures that the sanitiser can concentrate on killing bacteria and algae during these cooler seasons.&nbsp; </span></p></p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                            <div class="slides">
                    <div class="img"><img src="https://s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com/zodiac-au-2/Blog/5_steps_winter_prep/pool_jets.jpg" alt="Ensure all your equipment works" /></div>
                    <div class="text">
                        <p class="__blue">Ensure all your equipment works</p>
                        <p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Now</span><strong>,&nbsp;</strong><span style="font-weight: 400;">when you have finished preparing your swimming pool for cold weather, you need to clean the pool filters and all the equipment you have been running all summer. This will prevent germs and debris from spreading in your water. Any dirt such as scum or scaling left in the filter over winter will be a nightmare to remove when you want to start using your pool again. We recommend u</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">sing&nbsp;</span><a href="../filter-cleaner"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Zodiac's Filter Cleaner and Degreaser</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">&nbsp;to get rid of any clogs and grease in the filter.</span></p></p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                            <div class="slides">
                    <div class="img"><img src="https://s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com/zodiac-au-2/Blog/5_steps_winter_prep/man_using_pool_cover.jpg" alt="Cover your pool" /></div>
                    <div class="text">
                        <p class="__blue">Cover your pool</p>
                        <p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">A Fully waterproof pool cover would be best for the colder seasons to avoid any leaves and debris getting into the pool. Also make sure you reduce the pump/ filter running time and the chlorinator levels accordingly.</span></p></p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                            <div class="slides">
                    <div class="img"><img src="https://s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com/zodiac-au-2/Blog/5_steps_winter_prep/man_next_to_pool.jpg" alt="Check every 2 weeks" /></div>
                    <div class="text">
                        <p class="__blue">Check every 2 weeks</p>
                        <p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Over the winter, check the pool water chemistry once every 2 weeks. Check water level and adjust where necessary. Keep clearing skimmer baskets and it is a good idea to remove the pool cleaner from the pool to stop it being deteriorated. Also, check the filter gauge to see if another backwash is needed. This way you can ensure that you stay on top of any issues when you&rsquo;re ready to </span><a href="../opening-your-pool-for-the-season"><span style="font-weight: 400;">reopen your pool</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span></p></p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                    </div>
        <div id="counter"></div>
    </div>
</div>

        
     
                                <div class="content-block blog-styling">
                            <p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Winterizing the pool may require some effort but it will definitely make it easier for you to open up your pool for the spring &amp; summer seasons!</span></p>
            </div>

        
     
